##Hank Storage SMB Share + Permissions Fix

#Overview
Configured /mnt/storage 4TB SATA HDD in Proxmox so it can be used as shared storage from Linux Mint over SMB Samba

The goal was to stop relying on CLI file movement directly on Proxmox and make storage usable 
through the Mint file manager for normal drag-and-drop transfers, media access, screenshots, 
lab files, ISOs, and backups.

#Problem
the storage drive was mounted and usable for the command line, but most folders were owned by root:root 
with standard 755 permissions.

Example before fix
drwxr-xr-x root root /mnt/storage/media
drwxr-xr-x root root /mnt/storage/iso
drwxr-xr-x root root /mnt/storage/lab-files

This meant root could write to the folders, but normal SMB users could not reliably create, move, or manage files 
from another machine.

One folder also had odd ownership:
drwxrwxr-x 2 775 user /mnt/storage/transfers

That showed a numeric UID as the owner, which was messy and needed cleanup.
Existing Folder Structure
The folders already existed inside /mnt/storage:
dump
iso
lab-files
lost+found
media
screenshots
snippets
template
transfers
vm-backups

I did not recreate the folders. I fixed permissions on the existing structure.

##Permission Strategy
Created a shared group:
groupadd -f storage
Changed the storage directory and most subfolders to use:
root:userstorage
Set directories to use group inheritance:
chmod 2775

The important part is the 2 in 2775, which sets the setgid bit. 
That makes new files and folders inherit the userstorage group.
Final folder permissions looked like this:
drwxrwsr-x+ root storage /mnt/user-storage
drwxrwsr-x+ root storage /mnt/user-storage/media
drwxrwsr-x+ root storage /mnt/user-storage/iso
drwxrwsr-x+ root storage /mnt/user-storage/lab-files
drwxrwsr-x+ root storage /mnt/user-storage/transfers

The + shows ACLs are active.
lost+found was left mostly alone because it belongs to the filesystem itself:
drwxrwx---+ root root /mnt/storage/lost+found

##ACL Fix
Installed ACL support and added default permissions so new files should remain group-writable:
apt install -y acl
setfacl -R -m g:storage:rwx /mnt/storage
setfacl -R -d -m g:storage:rwx /mnt/storage

This helps prevent future permission problems when files are copied in from different machines.

Samba Configuration
Originally, Samba only shared the transfers folder:
[user-transfers]
    path = /mnt/user-storage/transfers
    browsable = yes
    read only = no
    valid users = user
    create mask = 0664
    directory mask = 0775
Added a new full-storage share:
[userStorage]
    path = /mnt/user-storage
    browseable = yes
    read only = no
    valid users = user
    force group = storage
    create mask = 0664
    directory mask = 0775
    force directory mode = 2775
    inherit permissions = yes
    inherit acls = yes
Also updated the existing transfer share to use the same group behavior:
[user-transfers]
    path = /mnt/user-storage/transfers
    browseable = yes
    read only = no
    valid users = user
    force group = userstorage
    create mask = 0664
    directory mask = 0775
    force directory mode = 2775
    inherit permissions = yes
    inherit acls = yes
Checked the Samba config with:
testparm

Samba loaded the config successfully.
Restarted Samba:
systemctl restart smbd
  
Shares Created
Two useful SMB shares are now available:
userStorage     = full shared storage drive
user-transfers  = quick transfer/drop folder

Client Connection
From Linux Mint, connected to:
smb:/IP/Storage

Final Status
Drive mounted:              /mnt/user-storage
Permissions fixed:          yes
Shared group:               storage
ACLs enabled:                yes
Samba configured:            yes
Full storage share:          Storage
Transfer-only share:         user-transfers
Mint drag-and-drop working:  yes

Lesson Learned
Linux storage permissions matter a lot once a drive becomes shared storage. 
A folder can be mounted correctly and still be annoying to use if everything is owned by root:root.

The clean solution was not chmod 777. The better setup was:
shared group + setgid directories + ACL defaults + Samba force group
That keeps the share usable while avoiding permission chaos.

